{{Infobox power station | name = Aitken Spence Power Station | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | location_map_alt = | coordinates = | country = Sri Lanka | location = [[Muthurajawela]] | status = U | construction_began = December 2016 | commissioned = 2019 | decommissioned = | cost = [[United States dollar|US$]]98 million | owner = [[Aitken Spence]] | operator = {{Nowrap|Western Power Company Ltd}} | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= | ps_thermal_capacity = | ps_heating_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = 11.5 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_storage_hours = | ps_annual_generation = 86.25 [[GWh]] | ps_annual_gen_year = | website = | extra = }}
The '''Aitken Spence Power Station''' (formerly referred to as the '''Meethotamulla Power Station''') is a [[municipal solid waste]]-fired [[thermal power station]] currently under construction at [[Muthurajawela]], [[Sri Lanka]]. It was originally planned to be built at Meethotamulla, the site of a large solid waste landfill which was under international media spotlight after the [[2017 Meethotamulla landslide|2017 Meethotamulla garbage landslide]] which killed over 30 people. The power station will operate approximately 7500 hours a year, utilizing the {{Convert|700|MT|lb|lk=on}} of fresh waste from the [[Colombo Municipal Council]] area, daily.<ref name="EarthWatts">{{cite web|title=Western Power Company Limited|url=http://www.earthwatts.com/westernpower.html|website=Earthwatts.com|publisher=Earthwatts Lanka Private Limited|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref name="DailyFT">{{cite news|title=Two waste-to-energy plants to get off the ground today|url=http://www.ft.lk/article/634380/Two-waste-to-energy-plants-to-get-off-the-ground-today|accessdate=8 October 2017|publisher=[[Daily FT]]|date=10 August 2017}}</ref> The power station in being built together with the [[KCHT Power Station]].
The facility will generate {{Nowrap|11.5 [[megawatt]] (MW)}} of power, of which {{Nowrap|9.7 MW}} will be sold to the state-owned [[Ceylon Electricity Board]],<ref name="EarthWatts" /> at a rate of {{Nowrap|[[Sri Lankan rupee|Rs]]. 37.10 per [[KWh]]}} generated.<ref name="DailyFT" /> Construction of the {{Nowrap|[[United States dollar|US$]]98 million}} power station began on {{Nowrap|10 August 2017}}, and is expected to complete by mid-2019. It will be operated by {{Nowrap|Western Power Company Limited}}, a subsidiary of [[Aitken Spence]].<ref name="DailyFT" /> The power station's [[Public Utilities Commission of Sri Lanka|PUCSL]] energy license is EL/GS/13-03.<ref>{{cite web|title=Current Licensees - PUCSL|url=http://pucsl.gov.lk/english/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Current_Licensees_updated_on_14July2017.pdf|website=[[Public Utilities Commission of Sri Lanka]]|accessdate=8 October 2017|page=4|format=PDF|date=14 July 2017}}</ref> {{Clear}}
