[[File:The path through Borsdane Wood (geograph 2417498).jpg|thumb|The path through Borsdane Wood]] '''Borsdane Wood''' is an [[Ancient woodland|Ancient Semi Natural Woodland]] in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]] and [[Metropolitan Borough of Bolton]], [[Greater Manchester]], England. It is believed to have been continuous woodland cover since before 1600 AD and is composed of native tree species that have not obviously been planted. Borsdane Wood was designated a [[Local Nature Reserve]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/Special/lnr/lnr_details.asp?C=18&N=&ID=57|series=Local Nature Reserves|title=Borsdane Wood|publisher=Natural England|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724020319/http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/Special/lnr/lnr_details.asp?C=18&N=&ID=57|archivedate=2011-07-24|df=}}</ref>
The wood consists of approximately 34&nbsp;hectares (85 acres) of mixed broadleaf trees including species such as oak, ash, birch, cherry, hazel, hawthorn, blackthorn and dog rose, as well as areas of open ground. With trees many hundreds of years old the wood has remained relatively unchanged for centuries and is home to a wide variety of wildlife. The wood follows the course of the [[Borsdane Brook]] which is the boundary between [[Hindley, Greater Manchester|Hindley]] and [[Westhoughton]] and the Metropolitan Boroughs of Wigan and Bolton. The brook flows through [[Wigan]], [[Pennington Flash Country Park|Pennington Flash]] and into the [[Glaze Brook]].
From [[Hindley, Greater Manchester]] there are several entrances to the wood, one of which can be accessed from Hindley centre through Raynor Park or through the cemetery. A tunnel under the railway leads into woodland little changed in centuries. A path leads to [[Aspull, Greater Manchester]] where the access is located near the Gerrard Arms [[Public House]].
The town of [[Westhoughton]] is adjacent to the wood.
